This may not directly answer your question but your use-case can actually be implemented using a combination of records and interfaces, eg:

```java
public interface Base {
   String prop1();
}
public interface Extended extends Base {
   String prop2();
}
record BaseR(String prop1) implements Base { }
record ExtendedR(String prop1, String prop2) implements Extended { }
```
You&#39;d code your &quot;client&quot; against the interfaces, which is an OO best practice anyway.  If you feel unhappy about duplicating `prop1` (and presumably other properties) in both records, you could use a single record with an overloaded constructor, as follows:
```java
record Record(String prop1, String prop2) implements Extended { 
	Record(String prop1) {
		this(prop1, null);
	}
}
```
This allows constructing instances reasonably cleanly:
```java
Base base = new Record(&quot;prop1&quot;);
Extended ext  = new Record(&quot;prop1&quot;, &quot;prop2&quot;);
```

Since your client is coded against `Base` and `Extended` (it knows nothing about `Record`), there&#39;s no risk of it accessing unsupported properties.

